{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492504"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:33:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:33:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1083"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1083","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1083"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.1,0.72,0.1,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1083"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56262"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1083","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1083"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1083"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41815"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"214"},{"type":"tags","id":"1149"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5967"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7942"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15075"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17326"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17383"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41677"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56262","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56262"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of a painless swelling in the left side of his scrotum. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The left side of the scrotum is visibly enlarged compared to the right. The swelling is non-tender on palpation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following examination findings would help to confirm the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Loss of cremasteric reflex","Inability to palpate the spermatic cord","Positive transillumination","Mass separate from the testis","Absence of a cough impulse"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn the evaluation of a painless scrotal swelling, careful inguinoscrotal examination is critical to differentiate between various possible causes. After establishing that the mass is painless, the next most helpful step is \u003Cstrong\u003Epositive transillumination\u003C/strong\u003E. A positive transillumination test indicates the presence of a fluid-filled structure, which in this case is most likely a hydrocele. This finding significantly narrows down the differential diagnosis and guides further management, which may include ultrasound for confirmation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELoss of cremasteric reflex\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily associated with testicular torsion, an acute and painful condition that doesn\u0027t match this patient\u0027s presentation of a painless swelling present for two weeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInability to palpate the spermatic cord\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically associated with hydrocele and wouldn\u0027t be as helpful in confirming the diagnosis. In fact, the spermatic cord should still be palpable in most cases of hydrocele.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMass separate from the testis\u003C/strong\u003E could be consistent with a hydrocele, but it\u0027s not as specific or confirmatory as positive transillumination. This finding could also be present in other conditions such as epididymal cysts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbsence of a cough impulse\u003C/strong\u003E is useful in ruling out an inguinal hernia, but it doesn\u0027t provide as much diagnostic information as positive transillumination for this presentation. A hydrocele would also not have a cough impulse, but this negative finding is less confirmatory than the positive finding of transillumination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter confirming positive transillumination, further characterisation with ultrasound would typically be the next step to definitively diagnose the hydrocele and rule out other less common causes of painless scrotal swelling.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Transillumination is a key diagnostic step in evaluating painless scrotal swellings, helping to differentiate hydroceles from other causes.","Careful inguinoscrotal examination is critical in differentiating between various causes of scrotal masses."],"references":["Langan RC, Puente ME. Scrotal masses. Am Fam Physician 2022 Aug;106(2):184-9. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2022/0800/scrotal-masses.html","Montgomery JS, Bloom DA. The diagnosis and management of scrotal masses. Med Clin N Am 2011 Jan;95(1):235\u201344. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21095426/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41815"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1083"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41815"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-19T21:35:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-19T21:37:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1083"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56262"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{